<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-MIGRATION _ HAVANA _ The ever-smoldering war of words
between Cuba and the U.S. over immigration policies is flaring up
again after the shark-eaten bodies of two Cuban men were found off
the Florida Keys in August. Cuban officials charge that the U.S.
Cuban Adjustment Act encourages Cubans to risk the perilous voyage
across the Florida Straits by granting automatic asylum to any
Cuban who sets foot on U.S. soil. U.S. officials, meanwhile, say
the Cuban government has been blocking Cubans with proper visas
from emigrating. We profile the controversy, hopefully by finding
Cubans willing to talk about their problems in trying to obtain
visas. NOTE: This could prove difficult, and many interview
subjects are likely not going to agree to be named, for obvious
reasons. (Williams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move Thursday on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JOURNAL _ MOSCOW _ How long does a superpower remain a
superpower? Ten years ago, the Soviet Union was dissolved, but many
Russians continue to believe their country is a great nation.
Adults proudly extend as proof Russia's high education levels,
industrial base, art and culture, and of course, their nuclear
arsenal. But as the remnants of this Soviet past rust and fade
away, what does the next generation of Russians, who grew up after
the end of the Cold War, believe? We spend a day in one of Moscow's
public schools to find out. Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move Thursday on the NYT Wire in both International
and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-FINAL-ANSWER _ CALCUTTA _ A look at India's obsession with
its locally produced version of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
and its impact on the biggest winner so far. (Basu, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-VOTE _ Democrats are banking on a strong turnout from
African American voters to match gains in 1998 and help Vice
President Gore carry a handful of Southern states. But without the
benefit of President Clinton's impeachment, which drove record
African American turnout two years ago, they are turning to a pot
pourri of local issues that they concede don't have the potency of
impeachment. Inititial hopes that Gov. Jeb Bush's re-organization
of Florida affirmative action programs would spark turnout are
fading. In Georgia, Democrats will have to motivate African
American voters without the presence of any African Americans on
the statewide ballot. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD _ PACTLOUS, N.C._ Tens of thousands of North Carolinians,
including Jackie Wilson, have yet to return to their homes a year
after Hurricane Floyd flooded much of the eastern portion of the
state. The high water soaked Wilson's house in Pactlous, east of
Greenville, but with several thousands of dollars in government aid
and charitable contributions, she was prepared to refurbish her
home. But workers discovered termite damage, raising the cost of
restoration to $50,000. So she moved a mobile home next to her
house, but county inspectors wouldn't allow her to hook up sewage
services because her septic system was outdated. So, she's back to
paying apartment rent. So many others face such obstacles that it
may be three to five years before Floyd victims return to permanent
homes, relief officials say. Some of those moving back into homes
are so financially strapped, said Methodist disaster relief
official Cliff Harvell, they are ``sleeping on the floor or eating
on the floor.'' (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 40 inches.
WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-INSURANCE _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _The number of Pitt County
residents with flood insurance has nearly doubled since last year's
flooding, but program proponents say more people still need
coverage. (Greenville Daily Reflector)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ELECTION _ WASHINGTON _ When it comes to high-tech issues,
who would make the better president: George W. Bush or Al Gore?
While the race for the White House won't be won by the candidate
who best clears the high technology hurdles, those concerns are
playing an ever-larger role in shaping the nation's economy. An
in-depth look at what Bush and Gore have had to say on the
technology front reveals fewer conflicts than similarities. (Glass,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With TECH-ISSUES _ Where the candidates stand on key points.
</P>
<P>
   With TECH-MONEY _ Tech contributions to candidates and parties.
