<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   BOOKMAN-COLUMN _ The push for school vouchers is a folly founded
on a fallacy. For the most part, it's driven by an ideology that
argues that government can do nothing right, that every
public-policy problem can be solved by turning it over to private
enterprise. Newt Gingrich used to capture that attitude perfectly
when he derisively referred to public schools as ``government
schools.'' (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Will resume next week. (Kleinberg, Cox News
Service.)
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _WASHINGTON _ In 1996, a friend ran across
Madeleine Albright at the Democratic National Convention as she
strolled down Chicago's Miracle Mile with her security guards in
tow. ``I hear you've got a good shot at being Secretary of State,''
the friend said. Albright pressed a finger to her lips. ``Don't
talk about it,'' she pleaded. ``It could screw things up.'' That
encounter came to mind at a recent dinner party attended by Richard
Holbrooke, Albright's successor as U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations and a leading candidate to succeed her as secretary should
Al Gore move into the White House next year. (Glass, Cox News
Service) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   ENTRY-LEVEL _ We'll look at the new entry-level worker. They're
young, cocky, well-paid, in high demand, and lacking many of the
job-search etiquette and creativity the old timers used to employ.
(Mallory, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (WITH ILLUSTRATION)
</P>
<P>
   CCE-ALM _ATLANTA _John Alm has some big shoes to fill as
president of Coca-Cola Enterprises. Replacing Henry Schimberg, the
Michael Jordan of the beverage industry according to one analyst,
will not be easy. Schimberg, who started out as a route driver and
retired at the end of last year after spending more than four
decades in the industry, is widely credited with turning
Atlanta-based CCE into the Coke system's premier bottling
organization. After buying concentrate or syrup from Coca-Cola Co.,
a bottler adds water and carbonation, then fills cans and bottles
with the soft drinks before distributing them to retailers. During
the 1990s, Schimberg and Chairman Summerfield Johnston Jr. nearly
tripled the size of the company through a series of acquisitions in
North America and Europe that boosted revenue to more than $14
billion. With nearly 70,000 employees in eight nations, CCE
currently accounts for three-quarters of Coca-Cola's case sales in
North America and 22 percent globally. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ALM-CAMP _ HYATTVILLE, Wyo. _ Toya Williams never rappelled down
a mountain before. Jason Harrison never rode a horse. And Christina
Edwards never shot a bow and arrow. All that changed this summer
when the Los Angeles middle school graduates stayed at a cattle
ranch in a picturesque mountain canyon just outside this town of
100. The three teenagers, and 33 others, were a world away from the
gangbangers and drug dealers that inhabit many of their inner city
L.A. neighborhoods. They were a world away from poor adult role
models, broken homes or inadequate supervision that made up some of
their lives. And they were a world away from having to worry about
where or when their next meal might come from. They were in summer
camp _ a special one created by someone they're likely never to
forget. That someone is John Alm, a high-powered, high-energy
beverage executive who spent several million dollars of his own
money to fulfill a long-term dream. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RADIO _ So, you can't pick up your favorite radio station
because you work in the bowels of a massive concrete building and
even the fiercest of radio waves can't penetrate those
AM/FM-defying walls? Big deal. You log on to the station's Web site
and tune in to your beloved disc jockeys, music and talk show hosts
right on your computer. Marconi never had it so good. (DiLonardo,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH RADIO-SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   EZELL- 401K _ After all the whooping about tax cuts, it looks
like one bill might actually become law this year. The bill _ up
for consideration in the Senate later this month _ would raise the
amounts that Americans can sock away in their IRAs and 401(k)
retirement plans. Here's a rundown on what it would do, and what it
would cost, and who it would benefit. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PAYDAY-LOANS _GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The number and amount of
high-interest ``payday'' loans - where you get money and the lender
promises not to cash your personal check until a certain date - is
exploding in western Colorado. Of the 14 licensed lenders in Grand
Junction, Clifton and Montrose, seven started doing business in
2000. In 1999, the companies made more than 21,000 loans for a
total of more than $2.8 million, according to the state. Statewide,
there were 600,000 such loans last year, for a total of $86.4
million, almost 30 percent more than in 1998. (Grand Junction)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   EPODSONE _ Not everyone who wants to use the Internet wants to
use a computer, so the consumer electronics industry is marketing a
growing number of what it calls Internet devices. One such device
is the ePodsOne, a portable tablet-like unit that allows the user
to browse the Internet and send and receive e-mail from anywhere a
phone jack is available. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
