<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   KNIGHT-LEGEND _ THE LEGEND AND THE FALL: The word began leaking
through the college basketball nation at 3 p.m. on Sunday, Sept.
10: Indiana basketball coach Bobby Knight, who had violated his
zero tolerance policy, had been fired. The chain reaction that
followed stopped the state of Indiana in its tracks. Students
protested and were arrested. Threats were made to the parties who
made Knight's actions public. Players announced they would quit if
their ultimatums were not heeded. Assistant coaches said they would
heed Knight's advice on whether to remain at the school. School
administrators tried to weather the storm. And Knight, with three
national titles, seemed to incite the masses on campus and during a
Wednesday night ESPN interview. We chronicle Indiana's Longest
Seven Days. (Denberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-CHIPPER _ Last season, Chipper Jones killed the Mets in
September en route to winning the National League MVP award. But
this is another year and now the expectations are even higher. As
the Mets and Braves open a run of six crucial games, Chipper is
struggling. Is it because he is trying to live up to the six-year,
$90-million contract he signed in August? With the NL East lead at
stake, the Braves and Mets open a three-game series Monday at
Turner Field. (Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-BRAVES _ A game-by-game look back at the six games
between the Braves and Mets last September. New York was only a
game back going into the first game. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OTHER
</P>
<P>
   HANDLING-TRAGEDY _ How has the city of Charlotte and the
Carolina Panthers football organization dealt with the tragedies
that have hit the city in recent years? The Panthers have had to
deal with the media frenzy surrounding the arrest of former
first-round pick Rae Carruth and the sudden death last summer of
former running back Fred Lane. And the tragedies haven't been
limited to the football team - last year's death of Charlotte
Hornets player Bobby Phills and the death of two fans at Lowe's
Motor Speedway in Charlotte two years ago. Through the first two
weeks of the season, the off-the field occurrences apparently
haven't impacted the team on the field as the Panthers are 1-1
heading into Sunday's game against the Falcons. But we will attempt
to gauge the interest in Charlotte and see if the town's sports
fans, who have been hit with several tragedies, are rallying behind
the Panthers. (Sugiura, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
