FILM DIRECTORS CALL FOR CLEARER RATINGS &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Directors Guild of America, stung by
widespread criticism that Hollywood sells violence to children,
called for a uniform ratings code for all entertainment media that
would help parents monitor what their children see or hear.
</P>
<P>
   The guild's downtown press conference Thursday was in a response
to a Federal Trade Commission report issued this week that
chastised entertainment companies for marketing explicitly violent
or sexual movies, recordings and video games at younger audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than denouncing the FTC report as a stepping stone toward
government censorship, the DGA embraced the study's conclusions,
its support of First Amendment concerns and its call for
self-regulation rather than government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``No filmmaker wants his or her film to be seen by those for
whom it was not intended,'' said Rob Reiner, reading at a news
conference from the policy statement prepared by the guild's Task
Force on Violence and Social Responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call upon theater owners to employ a zero-tolerance policy
with respect to allowing underage children to enter the theater
playing a movie that has been deemed inappropriate for their age
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We further support an industry-devised code of conduct to
govern the marketing of movies intended for mature audiences, and
encourage all who produce and distribute such materials to develop
these policies as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Wes Craven, who directed the ``Scream'' horror movies, declined
to speculate on how those smash hits would have done at the box
office if ushers had kept out most underage moviegoers and the
advertising had been aimed strictly at adults.
</P>
<P>
   If there were industry-imposed regulations that restricted a
future fright movie's advertising reach, Craven said, ``I'm willing
to accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make films that are for 17 and over. In my mind the core
audience is 17 to 35,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Barclay, who directed many episodes of ``NYPD Blue'' and
now helms ``ER'' and ``The West Wing,'' said Hollywood sometimes is
blamed for societal ills because ``politicians are finding it
easier to quantify the marketing of films to children than to
quantify a lack of parental attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Barclay also directed the R-rated comedy ``Don't Be a Menace to
South Central While Drinking Your Juice in the Hood,'' a 1995 spoof
of coming-of-age ``hood'' movies that is thick with crude humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a 13-year-old tells me, 'I've seen that film 10
times,' it makes me cringe,'' Barclay said.
</P>
<P>
   The position paper offered no real details or mechanism for
implementation, but its general points included:
</P>
<P>
   _ One standardized ratings system for movies, TV shows,
recordings, video games and Internet entertainment to minimize
consumers' confusion
</P>
<P>
   _ More detailed information than the currently wide-reaching R
rating issued by the Motion Picture Association of America, which
encompasses everything from scattered obscene language to abusive
sex and extremely gory violence. Under the suggested system (whose
particulars have not been determined), a movie's ads and trailers
would explicitly state the type of objectionable content that
warranted its rating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marketing plans that aim the product at its intended audience,
not a younger crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the MPAA, was traveling Thursday and
could not be reached for comment. Other representatives of the
association declined to discuss the DGA proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti will speak at related upcoming hearings of the Senate
Commerce Committee chaired by John McCain, R-Ariz., and studio
chiefs _ none of whom appeared at Wednesday's hearings in
Washington _ have been asked to appear in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Recording Industry Assn. of America and
the Interactive Digital Software Assn. did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report and the task force's formation in June 1999 grew
out of an outcry about the apparent negative impact of
entertainment violence on teens and children after the Columbine
High School shootings in April 1999 and other recent acts of
violence by children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
