<SLUG> BC-PAYLESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET INCOME AT PAYLESS CASHWAYS RISES 37% IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Payless Cashways Inc. turned in a mixed but
mostly positive quarter for the three months that ended Aug. 26,
earning 12 cents a share compared with 9 cents a share last year.
</P>
<P>
   Net income was $2.4 million, a 37 percent boost over net income
of $1.7 million in last year's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   However, same-store sales for the home improvement retailer fell
18.6 percent, mostly due to deflation in lumber and wallboard
prices, reductions in advertising activity and continuing business
restructuring. Same-store sales are sales at stores open at least
one year.
</P>
<P>
   Total sales were $392 million, compared with $492 million for
the same quarter last year, a drop of more than 20 percent. The
company had four fewer stores in the just-ended quarter than in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company managed to squeeze $23.3 million out of selling,
general and administrative costs, down to $84.7 million, a 21.6
percent improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The cash-flow measure EBITDA _ earnings before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization _ increased to $22.6 million, 5.8
percent of sales, compared with $22.4 million, 4.6 percent of
sales, for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Year to date, Payless has reported a 19.5 percent increase in
EBITDA, to $48.1 million, while the net loss narrowed to $1.7
million, a 69.5 percent improvement over the year-to-date loss of
$5.4 million for the first three quarters of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the first three quarters of 2000 were $1.16 billion, a
13.4 percent decline in same-store sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our third-quarter results reflect our many positive turnaround
initiatives as well as the negative effects of sector-slowing
dynamics,'' said the company's chief executive officer, Millard
Barron.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking about the improvements in EBITDA, selling, general
and administrative costs and better gross margins, Barron said, ``I
believe these fundamental improvements combined with our many sales
initiatives and a solid focus on building stronger relationships
with our target customers are key steps forward in our journey
toward a successful future for our company.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-00 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000915.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6179 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GIRLS-AGE-LADN     09-15 0633
