<HEADLINE>
KANSAS MAN IS AMONG TARGETS OF SEC CRACKDOWN ON INTERNET STOCK
SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An Independence, Kan., school bus mechanic
was charged last week in a nationwide crackdown on 33 companies and
individuals accused of using the Internet to defraud investors by
manipulating the prices of small companies' stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown by the Securities and Exchange Commission focused
on ``pump and dump'' schemes in which promoters hype stocks through
false contentions, pumping up their prices, and then sell the
shares at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said last week's sweep, its fourth against online
investment scams in the last two years, involved the stocks of more
than 70 thinly traded companies. The agency said the perpetrators
had made illegal profits of more than $10 million by pumping up the
total market value of the companies by more than $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What used to require a network of professional promoters and
brokers, banks of telephones and months to accomplish can now be
done in minutes by a single person using the Internet and a home
computer,'' Richard H. Walker, the SEC's director of enforcement,
said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinly traded microcap stocks are particularly susceptible to
online manipulations. ``That's why we have made this area one of
our highest enforcement priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15 enforcement actions brought by the SEC in Arizona,
California, Colorado, Florida, Kansas, Nevada, New York and
Oklahoma sought to curb the use of electronic newsletters, Web
sites, Internet chat rooms and e-mail to promote stocks through the
dissemination of false or misleading information.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said that many of the individuals and companies who
were targets of the crackdown had no experience in the securities
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Independence school bus mechanic, the SEC
alleged that Christopher P. Hastings, using the screen name
Stockpicks1, promoted the stock of 10 companies through a free
e-mail newsletter with up to 400 subscribers and on various
Internet message boards. The agency said Hastings included false
and misleading data concerning his track record for stock picks,
which he said averaged increases of 410 percent after his touts.
</P>
<P>
   In two instances, the SEC said, Hastings sold his personal
holdings of the touted stocks for profits of $70,309.
</P>
<P>
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Hastings last week consented
to an order barring him from future violations of federal
securities laws and agreed to give up $22,312. The order was filed
in U.S. District Court in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, 33, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Michael MacPhail, an attorney with the SEC's regional office in
Denver, said the consent order called for Hastings to pay $70,309
plus prejudgment interest, ``but we waived the rest of it based on
his demonstrated inability to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy typifies a trend of unsophisticated people without
any securities experience that are out there on the Internet
promoting stocks,'' MacPhail said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case brought by the SEC in New York, the agency charged
that Gursel Mandaci, a college student and driver for a car
service, purchased penny stocks using a margin account at an online
broker. He then posted messages on the Internet touting the stocks.
The SEC said Mandaci made more than $23,000 in six stocks,
including one whose price jumped from 1 cent to 38 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   In another case brought in Nevada, the SEC alleged that Chill
Tech Industry Inc. and its chief operating officer issued false and
misleading statements about Chill Tech's ``environmentally
friendly'' Arctic Can, supposedly a self-cooling beverage can. In
fact, the agency said, the Arctic Can used Freon, a banned
substance.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said that crackdowns in October 1998 and February 1999
dealt with the unlawful touting of publicly traded companies over
the Internet and that a May 1999 sweep focused on the sale of bogus
securities over the Internet. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
