r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-15 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSERTIONS OF SURPLUS ARE A LIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they turned off New York City's National Debt Clock
recently, a wire story said the decision was made because the
national debt ``has actually decreased since the beginning of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   No, no, no, no! A thousand times no! The Treasury's debt summary
dated Aug. 31 shows total public debt $5 billion higher than it was
on Aug. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, this number reflects laudable progress. It means
Washington has essentially balanced income and outgo for the past
year. In another respect, however, it reveals claims of budget
surpluses and declining debt as the fiscal shams they are.
</P>
<P>
   When July's Treasury report showed $4.8 billion in black ink, it
was cheered as that month's first surplus since the '50s, and the
year-to-date surplus for fiscal 2000 was put at $181 billion. Only
in the Wonderland of U.S. budgetary accounting, though, can anyone
claim a $181 billion surplus even as the national debt has actually
increased.
</P>
<P>
   While the Treasury calls all its obligations ``public debt,''
there are two kinds of debt. One component is marketable
securities, with market value, held by investors, financial
institutions and foreign interests.
</P>
<P>
   The other component is called nonmarketable debt. It is created
when the Treasury diverts revenue earmarked for specific activities
to other purposes. Revenue not needed to cover Social Security
benefits, for example, goes to finance general fund outlays. The
Social Security trust fund in turn receives a credit in the form of
a nonmarketable security _ an IOU with no market value. As such,
it's an unfunded liability of the U.S. government _ i.e., taxpayers
_ to be redeemed whenever Social Security revenue starts falling
short of benefit obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is merely the largest and most visible program
with more income than outgo, however. The national debt deception
involves focusing on the marketable debt and ignoring the
nonmarketable debt piling up in the form of myriad trust funds'
IOUs.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury has indeed been paying down marketable debt. On
Aug. 31, marketable debt was $3.056 trillion, or $224 billion lower
than a year earlier. Nonmarketable debt, however, is another story.
It stood at $2.611 trillion on Aug. 31, which was $229 billion
higher than a year ago. This means that despite Treasury's
marketable debt paydown, total national debt still rose slightly.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen? Revenue tagged for activities such as
Social Security, highway construction, air travel system
improvements, and myriad smaller programs having trust funds
generated more revenue than was spent toward their dedicated
purpose. The excess was spent on general budget items but still
counted as surplus even though the IOUs deposited in the trust
funds boost the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   When someone in Washington boasts of budget surpluses, Americans
should have but one response: Show us the money.
</P>
<P>
   The officially proclaimed budget surpluses for fiscal '98, '99
and 2000's first nine months total nearly $375 billion. The total
public debt outstanding during these 33 months has risen more than
$150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What we've got, it seems, is an accounting misunderstanding
amounting to more than half a trillion dollars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
