<SLUG> BC-KEYES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYES REITERATES TRADITIONAL VALUES MESSAGE IN BAKER UNIVERSITY
SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALDWIN CITY, Kan. _ Alan Keyes struggled to attract voters as a
Republican presidential candidate, but he did attract attention
with his ideas about the importance of traditional values.
</P>
<P>
   Holding to that message, Keyes received a standing ovation from
a crowd of about 800 who listened to his lecture Thursday at Baker
University's annual opening convocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had to choose between right and wrong,'' he said.
``There's never been a time when it's as important as it is (now)
and will become.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the economy prospers, Keyes thinks the United
States will succeed only if people and government are guided by a
code of decency and justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were founded on moral principle,'' he said at a news
conference after the address. ``If we lose our sense of that, our
institutions will fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, 50, ran for president this year and in 1996. He was the
Republican nominee for the U.S. Senate in Maryland in 1988 and
1992, and lost both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a classic political nobody,'' Keyes said. ``The fact that
I'm having any impact at all is a tribute to the grass-roots
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker spokesman John Fuller said the crowd Keyes attracted was
one of the largest in the history of the Loreine Collins Dietrich
Distinguished Lecture Series, which was established in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Previous speakers include former President Gerald Ford, former
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Republican vice
presidential candidate Dick Cheney and newspaper columnist George
Will.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Keyes, university President Daniel Lambert
described him as someone who ``seldom leaves any doubt where he
stands on important issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes said he would like to see the content of television shows
and movies cleaned up, but not by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to reform their products,'' he said, ``we should
reform our tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   When a student reporter suggested that today's young people are
uninterested in politics, Keyes disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience that's a myth,'' he said. ``But they want
substance, not shallow garbage fed to them.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
