<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEMCELL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL HEARS DEBATE ON USING U.S. MONEY FOR STEM CELL
RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scientists, famous film stars and influential
lawmakers said Thursday the potential for curing diseases justifies
using federal funds for embryonic stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   Russell E. Saltzman, a Kansas City, Mo., minister with diabetes,
begged to differ.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate committee heard testimony on legislation that would
allow researchers to use federal money to obtain stem cells from
leftover embryos created through the in-vitro fertilization
process.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cell research, which is legal if privately financed, has
shown promise in curing diabetes, Parkinson's and Alzheimer's
diseases, spinal cord injuries, heart ailments and other illnesses,
experts told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells are the basic cells in newly formed embryos that
generate all other tissues in the body. Some scientists think they
could use stem cells to create healthy tissue to replace diseased
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Michael J. Fox, Mary Tyler Moore and Jennifer Estess
testified in favor of the legislation, saying it could lead to
breakthroughs in the treatment of their illnesses. Fox has
Parkinson's disease, Moore has diabetes and Estess has amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   But Saltzman, pastor at Ruskin Heights Lutheran Church, told the
committee he would not want his diabetes cured if it meant
destroying an embryo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes to a question: Is the human embryo human life or is
it a mere bit of research material?'' Saltzman told the committee.
``If it is mere research material, then why should any human life
at any stage carry any special privileges?''
</P>
<P>
   Saltzman, asked to testify at the hearing by the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, was one of three witnesses who said
that destroying an embryo for research purposes is morally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Two senators at the hearing acknowledged the Senate is divided
as well, just as it was seven years ago when Congress decided
federal money could be used to pay for research using cells and
tissue from aborted fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should get the misimpression we don't wrestle with the
ethical and moral implications of what this is all about,'' said
Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa, ranking Democrat on the appropriations
subcommittee overseeing human services, which held the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Harkin, sponsor of legislation to allow federal money to be
used for stem cell research, said the embryos in question would be
destroyed anyway. Extra embryos are often created for multiple
in-vitro attempts for successful pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to be discarded, is it more moral and
ethical to use these to reduce human suffering and to prolong
life?'' Harkin asked. There are about 100,000 frozen embryos in
existence that will be discarded if not used, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin and Sen. Arlen Specter, the Pennsylvania Republican who
is chairman of the subcommittee, said they don't think of an embryo
as a human life. Moore said it ``has no more resemblance to a human
being than a goldfish.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saltzman said everyone came from an embryo, no matter the
circumstances of their conceptions. Saltzman said he was conceived
by step-siblings, perhaps through rape, and was put up for adoption
25 years before abortion became legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all once were human embryos, we all once were fetuses
quickening in our mothers' wombs,'' Saltzman said. ``We are all,
each, human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Heagy, a California man who became a quadriplegic after a
surfing accident at age 17, said he doesn't think tax dollars
should be used for embryo research, even if it may lead to progress
in treating spinal cord or other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not opposed to research,'' said Heagy. ``I'm not opposed
to walking again. I'm just opposed to the process.''
</P>
<P>
   A physician and research scientist with diabetes, Anton-Lewis
Usala, spoke of other effective ways to research and treat diseases
without have the government intervene in the fate of embryos.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, the perceived right of the government will
supersede the right of the individual,'' Usala said.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin, however, said his proposal addresses some of the moral
concerns. Embryos cannot be created for the purpose of research;
any fees would only be for transportation and actual costs involved
in the work; donors would have to sign written consents to permit
donation; and no one could be paid for embryos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new guidelines have established high ethical and
procedural standards that both federally funded and private sector
researchers would be expected to follow,'' Harkin said. The money
would come from the budget of the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the Senate leadership promised a vote on stem cell
research before adjournment next month. He has had film stars
testify at previous hearings to tell their stories, despite some
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make no apologies for this, because we need public
awareness of this issue,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, star of ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' of the 1970s, has
had diabetes for 30 years and has been at risk of blindness or the
need for amputation because of the disease. Moore said study has
shown that stem cells hold potential to develop insulin-producing
cells in diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that stem cell research should be pursued vigorously
and is appropriate for federal funding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox _ who recently received an Emmy for ``Spin City,'' the ABC
sitcom that he has left to devote more time to fighting his
neurological disease _ cited research he said indicates the value
of transplanted cells may have for patients with Parkinson's
disease and other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This research offers the potential to eliminate diseases and
literally save millions of lives,'' Fox said. ``It's time to act on
what we have learned. Further delay would come at a high price.'' (
30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-15-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
