<SLUG> BC-FUND-RAISER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED WAY TAPS FORMER DRUG DEALER FOR ROLE IN NEW CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ John Taylor, a former drug-dealing,
gunslinging high school dropout, once spent 17 months in prison for
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The United Way hopes he's still adept at getting money from
people.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is among those featured in television commercials and a
campaign video that the United Way thinks will tug at donors'
hearts in coming weeks and help it reach this year's $39.5 million
five-county fund-raising goal.
</P>
<P>
   The United Way's campaign video, in which a song plays over
images of people helped by United Way agencies, will be shown at
more than 2,500 area businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor appears with his daughter, JonNieca, 9. She's playing on
a slide. He's in a wheelchair, watching.
</P>
<P>
   He uses a wheelchair because he says the devil came to get him
nine years ago. Bullets tore into his neck and the back of his
head, leaving him paralyzed from the neck down. But the devil
didn't win, Taylor says. God did.
</P>
<P>
   United Way officials thought Taylor's bad-guy-turned-good-guy
story was so inspiring, they felt comfortable featuring him in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically do the same thing,'' Taylor, 32, says of the
United Way. ``We help others.'' Bad company
</P>
<P>
   John ``Fats'' Taylor, who grew up near 24th Street and Brooklyn
Avenue, dropped out of Central High School in the 1980s because he
would not graduate, even if he took summer school.
</P>
<P>
   One October, Taylor robbed some men at a coin-operated laundry.
When he returned from prison in 1988, his friends were selling
marijuana and crack cocaine. Taylor's job paid only $100 to $175 a
week, not enough for the lifestyle he craved.
</P>
<P>
   So Taylor sold marijuana, then expanded his inventory to crack
and ``water,'' the street name for PCP.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he and a friend were netting $700 an hour. They had gold
jewelry and cars. Taylor and his friends carried guns. So did their
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   One night Taylor dreamed he got shot. That, plus the fact his
girlfriend was pregnant, made him consider retirement.
</P>
<P>
   His nightmare came true first.
</P>
<P>
   It was the spring of 1991, 10 days before Taylor's 23rd
birthday. He had two passengers in the car, one of whom had just
spent 15 minutes inside an apartment, probably getting high.
</P>
<P>
   A handgun rested in Taylor's lap. The rear-seat passenger
carried two small-caliber handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fats, what do you want to do?'' the guy in the back asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want to do,'' Taylor answered.
</P>
<P>
   Pow! A bullet tore into Taylor's neck, instantly paralyzing him.
His uncontrolled car swerved into a parked car.
</P>
<P>
   Pow! Pow! Pow!
</P>
<P>
   Eight more bullets struck Taylor in the head, neck and shoulder.
He played dead, hoping the shooter wouldn't shove the gun into his
mouth for a final shot.
</P>
<P>
   As the shooter and the other passenger calmly walked away,
Taylor prayed: ``God, will you save me? Don't let me die like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, Taylor heard a woman whisper that there was
nothing they could do. His mother came into the room. She had been
crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Jr.,'' his father said, ``I love you. You was the
strongest son I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Was? Why did he say that in past tense, John wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Someone gave Taylor intravenous medication, and he faded from
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, at the Rehabilitation Institute of Kansas City, a
therapist asked Taylor his goals. Taylor wanted to walk out of the
United Way-funded institute someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, John, what do you really want to do?'' the therapist said.
``Realistically.'' Slow improvement
</P>
<P>
   As the years dragged by, Taylor improved slightly. He learned to
operate a motorized wheelchair. He regained some function in his
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   He also endured depression. He considered selling drugs again _
and for a while, got a girlfriend to do it for him. He smoked
marijuana when he could.
</P>
<P>
   He lived different places, including 18 months at Swope Ridge
Geriatric Center, another United Way agency.
</P>
<P>
   His faith wavered. Four weeks in a row, a minister showed up on
Sundays to take him to church. Three times, Taylor turned him down.
Finally, he said yes just to get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   At church, as members prayed for him, Taylor pretended to pray,
but he really wanted to get home to watch football. Then he felt
something kick in his stomach, as if it wanted out. His eyes flew
open. What had that minister done? Taylor felt scared.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, he began speaking at schools. He told youths
not to join gangs and not to sell drugs, or they could end up like
him.
</P>
<P>
   In the following years, Taylor gradually gained movement in his
right leg and toes. He experienced additional spiritual moments in
church services, including one Taylor took as God promising he
would walk again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by his birthday in mid-1999, Taylor feared his chances were
slipping away. Newly resumed therapy was going poorly. Taylor
stopped outside the Rehabilitation Institute and begged God to show
up and help.
</P>
<P>
   That day, he stood with the assistance of a walker with padded
arm rests and stepped as usual with his right foot. Therapist Renee
Hughes kicked his left leg along, as usual. Then she didn't kick
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor walked 60 feet without her help.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' said a surprised Hughes. ``Now we've got something to
work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside afterward, Taylor wept. And thanked God. Giving others
hope
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Taylor rolled his wheelchair into a
fourth-floor pod at the Jackson County Detention Center downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up, man?'' one inmate asked. ``We've been waiting for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone pulled a thick, worn Bible from Taylor's backpack as the
inmates scrambled to retrieve their own Bibles. Taylor flipped to
Genesis 22:1.
</P>
<P>
   An inmate read how God tested Abraham by telling him to
sacrifice his only son, Isaac, and how an angel stopped Abraham
just when he got out his knife. Abraham showed he feared God, so
God spared Isaac.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor equated the story to the inmates' situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only a test,'' he said. ``It's a test of several
things. It's a test of your faith. It's a test of your obedience.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor volunteers 14 hours a week at the jail, praying and
talking with inmates. He also spends more than five hours each week
at Swope Ridge, meeting with residents.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner Thursday, the Jackson County Detention Center
presented Taylor with a Volunteer of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   He works out twice a week at the Rehabilitation Institute. Part
of that time, he walks. With great effort, he pushes himself up
from his wheelchair and grabs the walker. Then slowly,
methodically, he plods down the hallway. The troublesome left leg
shakes as he strains to lift it. He looks down to see where it is.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Taylor experienced what he calls another miracle.
In his bedroom, he lifted his arms from his walker and stood
without support for 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and his visiting nurse cried.
</P>
<P>
   He has done more than doctors ever expected. Especially standing
alone _ something very rare for a quadriplegic, said Chris
Anderson, the Rehabilitation Institute's medical director.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor believes he will walk again someday without the walker.
</P>
<P>
   Then he wants to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing shall be impossible to them that believe,'' he said. (
30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
