<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS OPTIMISTIC AFTER PEREZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And now just in time for what promises to be an
intriguing offseason, a possible excuse for an ineffective Carlos
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez underwent successful arthroscopic surgery Thursday
afternoon to remove a chipped bone spur and clean up the base where
it calcified.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Jobe said the area had been sore for some time, and it
could be the reason why Perez had lost velocity the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible,'' Jobe said. ``There's no way to measure it,
but the thought did occur to me when we were doing it that could be
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll have more range of motion now, and it will
hopefully help him to regain his former glory.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Jobe and Dr. Ralph Gambardella should be enshired
immediately into the Medical Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was 5-8 with a 5.56 ERA before going on the shelf. This
after going 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers are still on the hook for $7.5 million
next year for Perez, the last season of his now infamous three-year
$15.6-million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe said Perez should be ready to start spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Subpoenas quashed: A Chicago judge quashed the subpoenas issued
to 18 members of the Dodgers organization and Alan Mills (since
traded to Baltimore) in the criminal case of Charles Carlin,
meaning none of the players will have to testify in the case, said
attorney Mike Abernathy. That trial begins Monday as Carlin faces
misdemeanor charges of disorderly conduct stemming from the May 16
fight at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Seven members of the Dodgers organization were subpoenaed in the
criminal case of Ronald Camacho, also charged with disorderly
conduct. A trial date hasn't been set for that, but Abernathy,
hired by the Dodgers to handle the cases, said he will argue those
subpoenas be quashed as well. ``It's the same thing,'' Abernathy
said. ``I don't see it as being a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgery for Leyritz: Reserve catcher Jim Leyritz will also have
arthroscopic surgery to repair a small tear in his right surgery
following the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, batting .200, will be available for pinch hitting until
the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   Pena improved: Catcher Angel Pena reported improvement Thursday
to the ligament strained to the outside of his left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   After an evaluation Thursday of his MRI, Jobe said the Dodgers
will let Pena go through complete pregame workouts to see if the
ligament shows continued improvement.
</P>
<P>
   If it does not, then Jobe said surgery will be required. Pena
said the thumb has been bothering him for two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know within two weeks if he'll need surgery,'' Jobe
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pena was the organization's minor league player of the year
1998, but reporting the next season overweight and lacking a strong
work ethic, he quickly grew into disfavor. Many, however, still
consider him the Dodgers catcher of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Last season in 120 at-bats, he hit just .208.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my chance last year,'' Pena said. ``I didn't play 100
percent. For now, give me a chance again and I'll be there 110
percent every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my fault.'
</P>
</TEXT>
