<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-AL-REDSOX-CLEVELAND-B     09-15 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-REDSOX-CLEVELAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX GET JOB DONE BEHIND PEDRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It has come to this: Baseball, Red Sox-style,
Thursday night became an exercise in mortal combat.
</P>
<P>
   Manning the point was the sniper, Pedro Martinez, chosen the
chief ``warrior'' by platoon leader Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him were the foot soldiers, led by the incendiary Carl
Everett (4 for 5, with a homer and three RBIs), keeper of the
mission statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be fearless and not care about our opponents,''
Everett said. ``Don't worry about offending them. That's the
attitude we have to take to the field: `I don't care what it takes
to win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And there was the enemy, the Indians, who got whacked by
Martinez, Everett, and the Red Sox, 7-4, as Boston moved within two
games of Cleveland in the American League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, before 42,709 at Jacobs Field, was Boston's third
in four crucial road games since the Sox were pasted by the Yankees
in a three-game sweep at Fenway last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The message? ``We are warriors,'' said Martinez, who allowed
three runs on only four hits and a walk over seven innings to
improve his record against Cleveland to 9-0. ``Nobody can take us
for granted. We are a team that fights back.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Sox flew out Thursday night for a four-game weekend
series in Detroit, while the Indians were bound for New York and
four games with the Yankees. The teams meet again next week for
five huge games in three days at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Williams likes what he is seeing. ``They're tough, they're
resilient,'' he said. ``They're battle-tested every day.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Martinez, Williams said, ``He's got the heart of a
lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez set the pace Thursday night, retiring the first 13
Cleveland batters before a crowd he said called him ``trash'' and
an array of profanities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just another day at the office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. It's not every game Martinez's bid for a
no-hitter is broken up so brutally. With one out in the fifth,
Martinez (17-5) issued a walk to Jim Thome.
</P>
<P>
   Then away went the no-hitter and shutout in one fell swoop. The
count was 1 and 1 to David Segui, who crashed Martinez's next pitch
into the right-center-field bleachers for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Segui had only three hits, and 11 strikeouts, in 23
at-bats against Martinez. And the Indians had gone 32 1/3 innings
without an earned run against their top nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to throw a sinker away,'' Martinez said. ``But the
sinker backed up on me and he hit it out. That's what you're
suppposed to do when somebody makes a mistake on you.''
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to some clumsy Cleveland defense and timely two-out
hitting by his teammates, Martinez was more than mighty enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox seized their first opportunity, with an assist from the
Indians. With two outs in the first, Everett reached on an infield
grounder that shortstop Omar Vizquel might normally have played for
an out.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra promptly took advantage by blasting a pitch by
Cleveland starter Charles Nagy for a double off the wall in
left-center to score Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox exploited another mistake in the third. Nagy, who was
involved in a memorable beanball incident with Martinez on April
30, opened the inning by hitting Lou Merloni in the arm with his
first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon's sacrifice bunt moved Merloni to second. He took
third on Jose Offerman's ground out and scored when center fielder
Kenny Lofton let Everett's high fly fall at his feet for a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to come in with your best against these guys,'' Nixon
said, ``or they're going to bury you.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Sox did the burying after Segui's bomb had cut
their lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no panic,'' Everett said. ``I just felt the way we
were going they couldn't stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   They broke it open with two outs in the sixth. After Nixon's
two-out single off Nagy, Offerman singled off reliever Justin
Speier, moving Nixon to third. Speier then threw a wild pitch at
Everett's feet, allowing Nixon to score to make it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then Offerman, who took second on the wild pitch, scored when
Everett deposited Speier's 3-and-2 pitch in the upper deck in
right, a 441-foot bomb that expanded the lead to 6-2. The homer was
Everett's 34th.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra followed with his second double of the night,
prompting Indians manager Charlie Manuel to replace Speier with
Chris Nichting. And the next batter, Troy O'Leary, lined to left,
scoring Garciaparra with the seventh run.
</P>
<P>
   Though Martinez said he had some of his best stuff of the year,
the powerful Indians lineup seemed to wear him down. Cleveland
touched him for a third run in the seventh after Roberto Alomar and
Manny Ramirez led off with back-to-back singles. A batter later,
Segui looped a single to right to score Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't dominating this team,'' Martinez said. ``I could have
easily lost this game if we didn't score, but I had a whole team
right behind me and that paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the team dared not take him for granted. ``He's the MVP
of this club,'' said designated hitter Dante Bichette, whose
fourth-inning homer gave the Sox a 3-0 lead. ``He's so valuable, I
don't even know if you can measure it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rod Beck on in relief in the eighth, the Indians scored on
a single by Vizquel and double by Roberto Alomar. But closer Derek
Lowe got the last out in the eighth and finished for his 34th save.
</P>
<P>
   As they packed up afterward, the Sox were wary of landmines
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency is to leave here on a high note and forget about
these four games in Detroit,'' Lowe said. ``Those are just as big
as the ones we just played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
